		<div class="qna-section">
			<div class="question">Question  4:Now coming to the most dreaded part of every recruitment process, describe your interview(s)(include projects)</div>

			<div class="answer">Answer: 
			<ul style="margin-left:20px">
			<li>For Mentor Graphics, it was around 45 minutes long interview on the Teams platform. It started with a general introduction about myself. Since Mentor Graphics is an EDA (Electronic Design Automation) company, there were a few questions on coding concepts related to C, OOPs and Python as well. So even though it seems like coding is not important in core companies but some companies do have a section in the online tests on coding concepts. Then I was asked to describe my college life with respect to the projects I did. I told them about Robolution Club and how we worked with different designs for our Throwing Bot to be used in the Robocon’20 Competition. I had also done a hardware design project using Verilog and the interviewer asked me to explain the project briefly. Then there were a few cross questions on the implementation of my projects. After that it was more like a rapid-fire questionnaire with questions ranging from VLSI Design to Digital Electronics. Many questions were focussed on differentiating between two concepts, different keywords in Python and C, or design styles. So, being thorough with the basics will help in dealing with such questions. </li>
			<li>For NXP Semiconductors, the Technical Interview round also began with a general introduction about myself. I was a bit nervous since the interview shortlist was announced just a few minutes ago and that too suddenly but I tried to keep myself calm as much as possible. Initially the questions were based on STA, DFT and VLSI Design, I was asked to explain different concepts in detail like metastability, latchup, why DFT is important, voltage and channel scaling in MOSFET, etc. Also, they asked me situation-based questions and I had to decide what kind of design is preferable in that situation or what will be the implication of using different parameters in a design, for example, I was asked – What will happen if the system clock is doubled while the network connection frequency is constant or Which ISA is preferred for memory accessing operations. For such questions, I will again repeat be thorough with the basics, such questions will have the simplest answer but if it isn’t in your mind, nothing will help in that moment. Then I was asked what was my favourite subject, I told them Computer Architecture. I was again asked few situation-based questions and basic questions on Computer Architecture. So, what I would say is that they wanted to test my understanding of the subject rather than how much I knew. They wanted to know whether I can implement what I know. Finally, they asked me about my project from internship at IIT Kharagpur. They wanted to know what was my contribution, what else I could have done to improve the project and what are my learnings from the project. I would suggest juniors to stay calm as much as you can during interviews and trust your basic knowledge because that is what is being tested.
			After the Technical Interview, there was a final HR Interview. It is very likely that if you reach this round you will be selected but do hold your horses, you don’t know what will happen so give your best and be as clear as possible while answering their questions. I was asked some questions on my family background and why I chose hardware and why not coding. Then he asked me which is my preferred location and concluded by saying “Hope you will hear some good news today”. In short, this round is basically to know about you and what are your future plans. So, stay calm and you will surely nail it.</li></ul>
